featured_reviews.review_text: Seats indoor were pretty comfy and food choices were aplenty. Crab was fresh and tasty! Fried kway teow ‘s wok hey is 👍🏻! Lime juice is a must-have to complete the meal 😋 Food were too enticing so we forgot to take some photos before tugging in 😅 Will return for other dim sum.

Had gathering with friends there. Food quality is good. Fresh ingredients. Crab vermicelli, steam fish otah, siu mai are good. Price is reasonable. 4 adults plus 1 kid, total was about $114. Peak hour may need to q a little while. Generally worth the price.

The food quality has dropped as compared to the one that closed in Geylang.

The fried food has come in smaller portions and over-fried.
Fried banana-mango only taste of mango and over-fried
Fried prawn roll had become smaller in size but still one of the better surviving food, over-fried as well
Fried chicken cutlet is ok with the chilli powder seasoning but still over-fried
Fried custard bun tasted like Kaya filling instead of custard.

The '饭菜' is dry and stale and had no sauce.

The '虾肠粉' is watered with oyster sauce instead of the soy sauce. Not as tasty

The wintermelon mix barley drink had also degraded. The taste is the same but the way the wintermelon is being marinated had differ.

Sorry but I'll patronise Tim Ho Wan, Swee Choon or others who serve consistent taste of food.

No, I won't come back again.

Will not be visiting again

1)Too Be Honest Never Ever Visit This Dim Sum Restaurant here bad Customer Services YOU WILL WAIT FOR A LONG WAITING TIME 2)Here is the Worst Dim Sum Restaurant waiting time just for the Chee Chong Fan need to take 40 Minutes,, 3) order Prawn had informed the Chinese males Staff 3 times still wait 40 Minutes to arrive comes out Porks Chee Chong Fan 4)ask to change a prawn Chee Chong fan the staff will tells you it s a Hand made you will need close to 1 hours just for a Simple Food 5)WILL BLACKLIST THIS PLACE NEVER VISITS HERE WITH YOUR FRIENDS OR FAMILY IF YOU WANT HAVE A NICE DINNER OR LUNCH

Service here is SO BAD. We came in at 125am, didnt know they closed at 2am until we sat (our mistake). They still seated us, and we were told last order. While walking to our seat, they mopped OVER our feet and acted like they didnt notice. Got seated and looked through the menu + placed our order within 5minutes. When food started coming, we tried 4 times to get the attention of staff to ask for red cut chili. We were being blatantly ignored, and even received multiple eyerolls at out request. Eventually had to get out of our seat to the counter to ask for the chili. While eating, they continued cleaning up (totally acceptable), but turned off the aircon while glaring at us. ??? Just to note, we left by 154am, and spent $95. This was an incredibly disrespectful experience. I understand that we came in late, however if you as an establishment is not happy to serve us or would like to close early / any other reason, you could simply voice it nicely and we would be happy to head somewhere else. Dont agree for us to dine here, then treat us like we committed a crime by stepping in. Aside from that, good was still good, and kitchen chef was actually respectful.

Food seems catered more to china audience now and not locals, which came to us as a shock that its not a local boss/manager manning the shop anymore. Its sad that ownership seems to have changed and quality dipped thereafter Only saving grace is their      which is their specialty and only good dish.

4/5 Super delicious - preserved egg and lean meat porridge Delicious - Prawn Dumplings, Siomai King, Lotus Leaf Rice, Salted Fish Lettuce OK - Fresh bamboo rolls (the overall taste is OK, but not as delicious as the ones from Donghai Restaurant. The fillings are a bit too hard) Not delicious - Xiaolong soup dumplings (the meat is too little and evaporated. The Tiantian noodles bought in the supermarket are 100 times better) The environment and service are also good - there are not many people and it is quiet. The food is served quickly. The waiter is not very skilled but has a good attitude and positive service. In addition, I read the reviews and found that many people said it was expensive. . I think the price is quite normal (it s better than some stores that are cheaper but taste less delicious) and a large pot of preserved egg and lean meat porridge (can hold four full bowls) only costs 5 yuan. What else do you want from a motorcycle ! !

It was my 1st time here so I can be more objective about this. The congee was pretty delicious for the price point. But portion size is huge. My first visit after the renovation.  Likely my last visit too. Before renovation, it looks decently like a dim sum place.  After renovation, there are nicer cushion chairs.  They also offer wine and alcohol with their bar like decor as well.  This combi does not work for me, but who knows, might work for someone else. Food wise, the taste is similar to pre-renovation.  Menu selection has shrunk. The portion of porridge CANNOT be ordered for one person.  There are only 2 person portion for porridge.  At dim sum places, I like to try different stuff and having a large portion of it at one go kind of makes it feel that its not a dim sum place. At around 6pm on a Thursday, the usual crowd is not there compared to pre-renovation times.  Before renovation, it would be around 80% filled with patrons, but now, only about 20% (and this is being a little kind, cause we were the only ones there till 2 other groups came in). Price wise, pre renovation, for comparison, you can have a sugar cane drink for SGD2.80.  For the same thing now costs SGD 4.30 That is >50% increase in price.  Granted that there are usually price increases, but >50% is not commonly seen. Overall, sadly no longer value for money.  I would have wished they did not spend money renovating and offered good food for a reasonable price instead.

Updates after renovation in 2023: The renovation was very much anticipated to end because it was a long 6 months. However, that may have also been the cause of the price hike that seemingly increased dish prices in the range around 50c to $1. Pork ribs has changed along side with the fan choy. It delivers a new style of presentation (added pandan leaf below and fried egg), wasnt necessary, wasnt asked for. But that could also constituted to the price hike. Portions are slightly smaller, spicy vinegar wonton was more like a Kway chup affair than a wonton with fillings. Spicy, perhaps isnt in it as well. Overall the quality has dropped, i would have preferred a traditional Cha Chan Ting with the old interior design they used to have, and the great cantonese dimsum. But that has changed, and the price hike didnt seemed to be attracting me for a subsequent visit moving forward. ------- Food seemed to be dominantly fried, lots of nice crispy wontons and dishes. Of course there are steamed dim sums, but yet their fried stuff is often what well get from them when were there. Place is not always packed also, so thats good. Best part is that it opens till late night, and not as packed like swee choon. But could do better with mkre steamed dishes!

Absolutely horrible experience at 126 yesterday night, spent $25 on 6 dishes and only 1 was nice. I came here once about 2 years ago and sad to say, the quality has dropped drastically. Personally would not recommend anyone to go. Ordered the spicy wanton in chili oil ($5.50 for 10 pieces) and you can see from the picture how miserably small it is. There were barely any fillings in it, and all I could taste was a small lump of meat and a lot of skin. The century egg in the porridge did not have any taste at all, and the porridge itself was super bland. The fan choy was bland, meat was dry and definitely tasted worse than the ones you can order at any kopitiam/coffeshops. 2 out of the 4 Har Kows skin was already ripped apart when the order came, and needless to say, they didnt taste good. Chicken feet was ok/not bad, and tasted super garlicky - i prefer the usual taste (YMMW on this). The beancurd prawn roll was the only nice item out of the 6 (although you need to pay $0.50 for mayo - think this has been the practice since a long time ago)

There are a few questions the foremost scientists of the world havent been able to answer. Is there life after death? How did the universe come to exist? And how is Swee Choon so popular when 126 Dim Sum is far superior to anything you can get there? 126 Dim Sum has amazing fried food; my personal favourite is the deep fried scallops. The fried mushroom fritters are solid as well. Also, dont miss the congee, which is flavourful and smooth, or the char siew chee cheong fun. Next time youre drunk after a night of partying and drunkenly crying/puking outside the club, make a detour and go to 126, either Geylang or Boon Keng. You wont regret it.

Orders are taken in such a way that you manually write in on a blank pc of paper and servers input your order into the system by manually keying in your order base on the scribbles you did on the paper.
